body:
## Steps to reproduce the issue

Given the following program:
```verilog
module evil;

    localparam [0:4] A = 5'b01100;
    localparam [0:3] B = 4'b1100;
    localparam [0:3] R = foo(A, B);

    initial begin
        $display("============ R=%x    =============", R);
        $display("============ R[0]=%x =============", R[0]);
        $display("============ R[1]=%x =============", R[1]);
        $display("============ R[2]=%x =============", R[2]);
        $display("============ R[3]=%x =============", R[3]);
    end

	function automatic [0:3] foo(
		input [0:4] argA,
		input [0:3] argB);
		reg [0:3] res;
        reg [31:0] i, j;
		begin
			res = 4'b0;
            for (i = 0; i < 4; i = i + 1)
            for (j = 0; j < 5; j = j + 1)
                res[i] = res[i] | ((argA[j] && argB[i]) && (i == j));
			foo = res;
		end
	endfunction

endmodule
```

Call `yosys evil.v -p 'hierarchy -top evil; proc' | grep ====` will trigger unexpected behavior.

## Expected behavior

I consider the following to be the correct answer for `R`, which is the same answer produced by `Verilator 4.216 2021-12-05`:
```
============ R=4    =============
============ R[0]=0 =============
============ R[1]=1 =============
============ R[2]=0 =============
============ R[3]=0 =============
```

## Actual behavior

Using `Yosys 0.12+57 (git sha1 0feba821a, gcc 11.1.0 -march=x86-64 -mtune=generic -O2 -fno-plt -fexceptions -fstack-clash-protection -fcf-protection -fPIC -Os)` yields:
```
============ R=c    =============
============ R[0]=1 =============
============ R[1]=1 =============
============ R[2]=0 =============
============ R[3]=0 =============
```

*Probably* "upto" buses are indexed in the reversed way by Yosys?

